essdate=June 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Recorded music retail sales===\n====2000====\nIn its June 30, 2000 annual report filed with the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]], Seagram reported that Universal Music Group made 40% of the worldwide [[classical music]] sales over the preceding year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.secinfo.com/dsvr4.58n4.htm#445 |title=Seagram Co Ltd - '10-K405' for 6/30/00 |publisher=SEC Info |date= |accessdate=November 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2005====\nInterim physical retail sales in 2005. All figures in millions.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Country info\n! colspan=\"4\" | Units\n! colspan=\"2\" | Value\n! colspan=\"2\" | Change (%)\n|-\n! Ranking\n! Country name\n! Singles\n! CD\n! DVD\n! Total Units\n! $ (in USD)\n! Local Currency\n! Units\n! Value\n|-\n| 1\n| USA\n| 14.7\n| 300.5\n| 11.6\n| 326.8\n| 4783.2\n| 4783.2\n| \u22125.70%\n| \u22125.30%\n|-\n| 2\n| Japan\n| 28.5\n| 93.7\n| 8.5\n| 113.5\n| 2258.2\n| 239759\n| \u22126.90%\n| \u22129.20%\n|-\n| 3\n| UK\n| 24.3\n| 66.8\n| 2.9\n| 74.8\n| 1248.5\n| 666.7\n| \u22121.70%\n| \u22124.00%\n|-\n| 4\n| Germany\n| 8.5\n| 58.7\n| 4.4\n| 71\n| 887.7\n| 689.7\n| \u22127.70%\n| \u22125.80%\n|-\n| 5\n| France\n| 11.5\n| 47.3\n| 4.5\n| 56.9\n| 861.1\n| 669.1\n| 7.50%\n| \u22122.50%\n|-\n| 6\n| Italy\n| 0.5\n| 14.7\n| 0.7\n| 17\n| 278\n| 216\n| \u22128.40%\n| \u221212.30%\n|-\n| 7\n| Canada\n| 0.1\n| 20.8\n| 1.5\n| 22.3\n| 262.9\n| 325\n| 0.70%\n| \u22124.60%\n|-\n| 8\n| Australia\n| 3.6\n| 14.5\n| 1.5\n| 17.2\n| 259.6\n| 335.9\n| \u221222.90%\n| \u221211.80%\n|-\n| 9\n| India\n| \u2013\n| 10.9\n| \u2013\n| 55.3\n| 239.6\n| 11500\n| \u221219.20%\n| \u22122.40%\n|-\n| 10\n| Spain\n| 1\n| 17.5\n| 1.1\n| 19.1\n| 231.6\n| 180\n| \u221213.40%\n| \u221215.70%\n|-\n| 11\n| Netherlands\n| 1.2\n| 8.7\n| 1.9\n| 11.1\n| 190.3\n| 147.9\n| \u221231.30%\n| \u221219.80%\n|-\n| 12\n| Russia\n| \u2013\n| 25.5\n| 0.1\n| 42.7\n| 187.9\n| 5234.7\n| \u22129.40%\n| 21.20%\n|-\n| 13\n| Mexico\n| 0.1\n| 33.4\n| 0.8\n| 34.6\n| 187.9\n| 2082.3\n| 44.00%\n| 21.50%\n|-\n| 14\n| Brazil\n| 0.01\n| 17.6\n| 2.4\n| 24\n| 151.7\n| 390.3\n| \u221220.40%\n| \u221216.50%\n|-\n| 15\n| Austria\n| 0.6\n| 4.5\n| 0.2\n| 5\n| 120.5\n| 93.6\n| \u22121.50%\n| \u22129.60%\n|-\n| 16\n| Switzerland **\n| 0.8\n| 7.1\n| 0.2\n| 7.8\n| 115.8\n| 139.2\n| n/a\n| n/a\n|-\n| 17\n| Belgium\n| 1.4\n| 6.7\n| 0.5\n| 7.7\n| 115.4\n| 89.7\n| \u221213.80%\n| \u22128.90%\n|-\n| 18\n| Norway\n| 0.3\n| 4.5\n| 0.1\n| 4.8\n| 103.4\n| 655.6\n| \u221219.70%\n| \u221210.40%\n|-\n| 19\n| Sweden\n| 0.6\n| 6.6\n| 0.2\n| 7.2\n| 98.5\n| 701.1\n| \u221229.00%\n| \u221220.30%\n|-\n| 20\n| Denmark\n| 0.1\n| 4\n| 0.1\n| 4.2\n| 73.1\n| 423.5\n| 3.70%\n| \u22124.20%\n|- style=\"FONT-WEIGHT: bold; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #ccc\"\n|\n| Top 20\n| 74.5\n| 757.1\n| 42.8\n| 915.2\n| 12378.7\n|\n| \u22126.60%\n| \u22126.30%\n|}\n\n====2003\u20132007====\nApproximately 21% of the [[gross revenue|gross CD revenue]] numbers in 2003 can be attributed to used CD sales.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}} This number grew to approximately 27% in 2007.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}} The growth is attributed to increasing on-line sales of used product by outlets such as Amazon.com, the growth of used music media is expected to continue to grow as the cost of digital downloads continues to rise.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}} The sale of used goods financially benefits the vendors and online marketplaces, but in the United States, the [[first-sale doctrine]] prevents copyright owners (record labels and publishers, generally) from \"double dipping\" through a levy on the sale of used music.\n\n====2011====\nIn mid-2011, the RIAA trumpeted a sales increase of 5% over 2010, stating that \"there's probably no one single reason\" for the bump.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/blog.php?content_selector=riaa-news-blog&blog_selector=Midyear-Digital-Music-Milestones&news_month_filter=7&news_year_filter=2011&searchterms=Music%20sales&terminclude=&termexact=|date=July 11, 2011|accessdate=October 18, 2012|title=Midyear Digital Music Milestones|quote=There's probably no one single reason, but we'd like to think that enhanced marketing efforts \u2013 like the sale of music at nontraditional outlets \u2013 and anti-piracy successes like the closure of LimeWire have helped.|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021050119/http://www.riaa.com/blog.php?content_selector=riaa-news-blog&blog_selector=Midyear-Digital-Music-Milestones&news_month_filter=7&news_year_filter=2011&searchterms=Music%20sales&terminclude=&termexact=|archivedate=October 21, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n====2012====\nThe Nielsen Company & Billboard's 2012 Industry Report shows overall music sales increased 3.1% over 2011. Digital sales caused this increase, with a Digital Album sales growth of 14.1% and Digital Track sales growth of 5.1%, whereas Physical Music sales decreased by 12.8% versus 2011. Despite the decrease, physical albums were still the dominant album format. Vinyl Record sales increased by 17.7% and Holiday Season Album sales decreased by 7.1%.<ref name=\"NielsenReport2012\" />\n\n===Total revenue by year===\nGlobal trade revenue according to the [[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry|IFPI]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Revenue\n! Change\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2005\n| $20.7 billion\n| \u20133%\n| <ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\">[https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2007/jul/03/news.musicnews Downloads fail to stem fall in global music sales] ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref><ref>Press Release: [http://www.ifpi.org/content/library/worldsales2005.pdf \"Digital Formats continue to drive the Global Music Market,\"] IFPI (London, March 31, 2006).</ref>\n\n|-\n| 2006\n| $19.6 billion\n| \u20135%\n| <ref name=\"guardian.co.uk\"/>\n|-\n| 2007\n| $18.8 billion\n| \u22124%\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://musically.com/2008/05/15/ifpi-reveals-2007-recorded-music-revenues-decline/ |title=IFPI r