-percent-global-drop|title= Global Record Business Dips Slightly, U.S. Ticks Upwards In IFPI's 2015 Report|last= Smirke|first= Richard|date= April 14, 2015|accessdate= April 20, 2015|work= [[billboard.com]]}}</ref>\n|-\n|2015\n|$15 billion\n| +3.2%\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7332929/ifpi-global-digital-music-services-revenue-growth-report|title=IFPI Global Report: Digital Revenues Surpass Physical for the First Time as Streaming Explodes|access-date=July 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ifpi.org/downloads/GMR2016.pdf|title=IFPI Global Music Report 2016: State of the Industry|website=Ifpi.org|access-date=July 22, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016\n|$15.7 billion\n| +5%\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/04/02/streaming-accounted-for-nearly-half-of-music-revenues-worldwide-in-2018/|title=Streaming accounted for nearly half of music revenues worldwide in 2018|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n|-\n|2017\n|$17.4 billion\n| +10.8\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/04/02/streaming-accounted-for-nearly-half-of-music-revenues-worldwide-in-2018/|title=Streaming accounted for nearly half of music revenues worldwide in 2018|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n|-\n|2018\n|$19.1 billion\n| +9.7%\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/04/02/streaming-accounted-for-nearly-half-of-music-revenues-worldwide-in-2018/|title=Streaming accounted for nearly half of music revenues worldwide in 2018|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==By region==\n* [[Music industry of Asia]]\n* [[Music industry of East Asia]]\n* [[Nordic popular music|Music industry of Northern Europe]]\n* [[:Category:British music industry|Music industry of the U.K.]]\n\n==Associations and organizations==\n<!-- NOTE: The format for organizations is:\n* [[Thai Entertainment Content Trade Association]] (acronym/abbreviation here - TECA)\nThank you.\n-->\nThe [[List of music associations and organizations]] covers examples from around the world, ranging from huge international bodies to smaller national-level bodies.\n\n==See also==\n{{col div|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[DIY ethic]]\n* [[History of music publishing]]\n* [[Independent record label]]\n* [[List of record labels]] and [[:Category:Record labels]]\n* [[List of best-selling music artists]]\n* [[MIDEM]]-World's largest music trade fair\n* [[Record label]]\n* [[Music community]]\n{{col div end}}\n{{Portal bar|Music|Business and economics}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n* {{Krasilovsky et al 2007}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Further reading|date=May 2016}}\n* Lebrecht, Norman: ''When the Music Stops: Managers, Maestros and the Corporate Murder of Classical Music'', Simon & Schuster 1996\n* Imhorst, Christian: [http://www.imhorst.net/?page_id=21 The 'Lost Generation' of the Music Industry], published under the terms of the [[GNU Free Documentation License]] 2004\n* Gerd Leonhard: ''Music Like Water \u2013 the inevitable music ecosystem''\n* The Methods Reporter: [https://web.archive.org/web/20070112051509/http://www.methodsreporter.com/2007/01/07/recording-industry-music-download-lawsuit/ Music Industry Misses Mark with Wrongful Suits]\n* [http://www.soc.duke.edu/~s142tm01/main.html Music CD Industry] \u2013 a mid-2000 overview put together by Duke University undergraduate students\n* [[Mario d'Angelo]]: \"Does globalisation mean ineluctable concentration ?\" in Roche F., Marcq B., Colom\u00e9 D. (eds)''The Music Industry in the New Economy, Report of the Asia-Europe Seminar'' (Lyon 2001) IEP de Lyon/Asia-Europe Foundation/Eurical, 2002, pp.&nbsp;53\u201360.\n* [[Mario d'Angelo]]: ''Perspectives de gestion des institutions musicales en Europe'' (Management Perspectives for Musical Institutions in Europe), OMF Series, Paris-Sorbonne University, Ed. Musicales Aug. Zurfluh, Bourg-la-Reine, 2006 {{